(41, 6, 4, 42, 4, 24, 24, 'a prophet is not without honour', 'Rejection of Prophets Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of acceptance of prophets in their own communities. This connection highlights the shared theme of a prophet''s honor being diminished among familiar people.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 4, 40, 13, 57, 57, 'A prophet is not without honour', 'Connection of Jesus'' Prophetic Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that a prophet is not honored in his own country and house. This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by Jesus from those familiar with him.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 4, 24, 12, 6, 6, 'a prophet is not without honour', 'Rejection of Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by prophets in their own communities. Both passages emphasize the betrayal and lack of honor that prophets experience from their own kin.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 4, 24, 11, 21, 21, 'A prophet is not without honour', 'Rejection of Prophets Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of prophets by their own people. In Mark, Jesus notes that a prophet lacks honor in his own country, while Jeremiah describes the men of Anathoth seeking to silence the prophet. This connection highlights the theme of local rejection faced by those who speak on behalf of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 5, 40, 13, 58, 58, 'no mighty work', 'Connection of Unbelief and Mighty Works', 'Both passages emphasize the limitation of Jesus'' ability to perform miracles due to the presence of unbelief. In Mark, the phrase ''could there do no mighty work'' reflects the same theme found in Matthew, where ''did not many mighty works there because of their unbelief'' indicates a direct correlation between faith and miraculous acts.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 5, 41, 9, 23, 23, 'mighty work', 'Connection of Belief and Healing', 'This connection highlights the relationship between belief and the ability to perform mighty works. In Mark 6:5, the lack of belief limits Jesus'' ability to heal, while Mark 9:23 emphasizes that belief enables all things to be possible.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 5, 41, 5, 23, 23, 'laid his hands upon', 'Healing Through Laying on Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying hands for healing. In Mark 5:23, the request is made for Jesus to lay his hands on a sick girl, while Mark 6:5 notes that he could only heal a few by laying hands. This connection highlights the significance of this action in the context of healing.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 5, 58, 4, 2, 2, 'no mighty work', 'Connection of Faith and Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of faith''s role in receiving God''s power. In Mark 6:5, the lack of faith limits Jesus'' ability to perform mighty works, while Hebrews 4:2 emphasizes that the gospel''s effectiveness is contingent upon faith in those who hear it.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 5, 23, 59, 1, 2, 'could there do no mighty work', 'Divine Power and Human Sin', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power being limited by human iniquities. In Mark, Jesus'' ability to perform miracles is hindered, while Isaiah emphasizes that sin separates people from God''s saving power.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 5, 1, 19, 22, 22, 'could there do no mighty work', 'Divine Limitations in Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine limitations in both passages. In Mark 6:5, Jesus could do no mighty work, while in Genesis 19:22, the angel could not act until Lot arrived, indicating a restriction on divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 5, 1, 32, 25, 25, 'laid his hands upon', 'Healing and Physical Struggle', 'This connection highlights the physicality of both passages, where healing and injury occur through divine interaction. In Mark, Jesus'' ability to heal is limited, while in Genesis, a physical touch results in injury, emphasizing the power and impact of divine encounters.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
